[!let lerp = (a, b, t) => a + (b - a) * t]
[!let ramp = (secs) => Math.min(elapsed() / secs, 1)]
[!let between = (from, to) => lines_since() >= from && lines_since() < to]
A live readout, so you can watch a signal move while you step. [browser_2d.text("elapsed " + elapsed().toFixed(1) + "s", 300, 80, 34, "white")]
Test one, a hold. This cube jumps big the instant the bracket fires, and drops back after three seconds. [!let a = browser_3d.cube(1, 1, 1, "blue", -3, 2)] [browser_3d.scale(a, elapsed() < 3 ? 1.6 : 1)]
Nothing switched it back. The expression just stopped being true.
Test two, a ramp. This sphere slides right over two seconds, driven by elapsed alone, with no duration argument. [!let b = browser_3d.sphere(0.5, 0.5, 0.5, "cyan", -3, 0)] [browser_3d.move(b, lerp(-3, 0, ramp(2)), 0, 0)]
And it fades up over three seconds, on its own separate clock. [browser_3d.opacity(b, ramp(3))]
Test three, the same motion twice. This one uses a built-in duration tween. [!let c = browser_3d.sphere(0.4, 0.4, 0.4, "orange", 0, 2)] [!browser_3d.move(c, 3, 2, 0, 2)]
This one uses elapsed instead. [!let d = browser_3d.sphere(0.4, 0.4, 0.4, "orange", 0, -2)] [browser_3d.move(d, lerp(0, 3, ramp(2)), -2, 0)]
Watch both. If they look the same, the engine tween and elapsed are two mechanisms doing one job.
Test four, nesting done wrong on purpose. This torus should grow when its gate opens, two lines from here. [!let e = browser_3d.torus(0.8, 0.15, "violet", 3, 0)] [browser_3d.scale(e, between(2, 4) ? lerp(1, 2, ramp(1)) : 1)]
Keep reading.
The gate is open now, but it snapped instead of growing: elapsed counts from when the bracket fired, not from when the gate opened, so the ramp finished while you were reading.
Keep reading.
The gate just closed, and it snapped back.
Test five, nesting done right. Put the driver on the line where the effect starts, so both clocks begin together. [!let f = browser_3d.cube(0.8, 0.8, 0.8, "lime", 3, -2)] [browser_3d.scale(f, between(0, 2) ? lerp(1, 2, ramp(1)) : 1)]
That grew over one second, because the gate opened at the same moment the clock started.
And now it has dropped, because the gate closed here.
Test six, the re-arm. Step backward up to line seventeen, then forward again: both of its clocks restart, and the cube grows from one all over again.
Test seven, deliberate breakage. Insert a new line anywhere between line seventeen and line nineteen, save, and step through again. The gate will now open and close at the wrong moments.
That is the weakness of counting lines to reach a distant moment, and the argument for naming moments instead.
Done. [RESET()]